INSERT INTO `nge_icl_strings` VALUES('5034', 'en', 'page-builder-shortcode-strings-469', '3737782ba40786d5b84926042681ee74', '</p>\r\n<p>When registering your business you need to know what status you want to register as.<br /><strong>Sole Proprietorship:</strong><br />Registering as a sole proprietorship means that one person owns and operates the business. This person owns the whole capital and receives all the profits of the company. It also means that allÂ obligations and liabilitiesÂ are the responsibility of the proprietor.Â A business registered as a sole proprietorship, according to theÂ Real Tax Regime, is considered as a small taxpayer.Â The problem with the sole proprietorship is the liability. If your business is small and risk of having large debts/liabilities is small, then registering as a sole proprietorship may be the best choice to pay less taxes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Partnership:<br /></strong>Two or more persons together can register as a partnership. This is legally similar to a sole proprietorship, however there are two or more people registered as business owners. It is advised to create a written partnership contract to minimise the risk of any issues that may arise. All the partners are responsible for any debts and obligations.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Limited Partnership:</strong><br />A limited partnership is similar to a general partnership, however one of the partners has âlimited liability.â This means that the partner that has limited liability is not personally liable for any debts and obligations. This may be the case when a partner wants to invest money into the business, but does not want to be personally liable for the business.. If a limited partnership is not notified to the Ministry of Commerce, it will be considered as a general partnership.<strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Private Limited Company:<br />This legal company status corresponds to the âtraditional enterpriseâ and is composed ofÂ shareholdersÂ and directors. Shareholders and directors are not personally liable for the companyâs debts. A private limited company is composedÂ ofÂ 2 to 30 shareholders.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>For more information and tips on how to choose a status, please seeÂ <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/choosing-your-business-status/\">âChoosing your business statusâ</a>Â under our Business Tips section.Â </strong></p>\r\n<p>', '8', '1', '', 'VISUAL', 'vc_column_text: content', '0', '', 'a9da75c899c48eb1bee504c53c4a8130', 'optional', NULL);
